> I think a [54de6e7](https://github.com/containers/podman/commit/54de6e7a96fd727cb5141ced4621d6220d65ec3c) client will not read outside of the context directory. A `podman system service` of [54de6e7](https://github.com/containers/podman/commit/54de6e7a96fd727cb5141ced4621d6220d65ec3c) may read outside of the context directory if some other client (for example Podman 4.3.1) performs a remote build. (Just mentioning it as a side-note as this PR touches the client-side code)

@eriksjolund Yes that is correct and expected that the older client version does not have this patch we will have to backport it on necessary versions and we already have ticket for those.

@containers/podman-maintainers PTAL

@eriksjolund  Overall I'm not sure about about supporting every third party client, I think podman can only guarantee about `podman-remote`, `docker`, `API` and `compat API`.  Do you think i missed any other client ?

Also if any third party client wants to process `symlink` and post it to podman via API it should still be allowed, cause they are using API directly, I don't think its a problem with `podman` but how a third party client has implemented it. But we can discuss on this.

We can actually make it work for API as well if we move parts of symlink validation from `func parseDockerignore` to server end but not sure if that is expected thing to do ? ( It prohibits use-case where someone actually wants to send symlink in build context for API use-case but it is still support by regular podman and buildah )

@eriksjolund That's a fair point if everybody agrees I think we can implement it on the buildah side in a different PR. This PR was majorly concern with the security issue of resolving symlink on host side only for `podman-remote` and `podman server`.

Overall I still think`buildah` running on host should resolv symlink but I have no strong opinion and okay to implement it on buildah side as a feature instead of security patch.

@eriksjolund other than that is there anything else blocking this PR ?
